'''Annette Jocelyn Otway-Ruthven''' (7 November 1909 – 18 March 1989) was an Irish [[historian]] specialising in [[History of Ireland (800–1169)|medieval Irish history]], and was among the earliest female academics appointed in [[Trinity College, Dublin]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Otway-Ruthven, Jocelyn (1909–1989) - Dictionary definition of Otway-Ruthven, Jocelyn (1909–1989) {{!}} Encyclopedia.com: FREE online dictionary |journal=Women in World History: A Biographical Encyclopedia |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/otway-ruthven-jocelyn-1909-1989 |accessdate=10 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>
== Family == [[File:Professor Annette Jocelyn Otway-Ruthven (1909-89).jpg|thumb|A.J.Otway-Ruthven (1909-1989) was appointed Lecky Professor of History in Trinity College Dublin in 1951 and was one of the first female Fellows.]] Otway-Ruthven was the daughter of Captain Robert Mervyn Bermingham Otway-Ruthven (1867–1919), Royal Artillery, of [[Castle Otway]], Co. Tipperary, and Margaret Casement (d. 1953), of Cronroe, Co. Wicklow. She had three sisters and a brother; two of her sisters died young. Through her mother Otway-Ruthven was related to [[Roger Casement]].
==Academic career== Otway-Ruthven studied history in [[Trinity College, Dublin]], was [[List of Scholars of Trinity College, Dublin|elected a Scholar]] of the College in 1928, and graduated BA in 1931. She continued her studies at [[Girton College, Cambridge|Girton College]], [[University of Cambridge]], writing ''The king's secretary and the signet office in the XV century''<ref>{{Cite book|title=The king's secretary and the signet office in the XV century|last=Otway-Ruthven|first=Annette Jocelyn|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1939}}</ref> for which she was awarded a PhD.
She returned to Trinity College in 1938 as lecturer in medieval and modern history and in economic history; she succeeded [[Constantia Maxwell]] as [[Lecky Professor of History|Lecky professor]] in 1951. From 1965 she headed a new department of medieval history which, under her direction, became one of the finest departments in the College. In 1968 TCD made her one of its first female Fellows. The position of female academics in Trinity College when Otway-Ruthven was appointed in 1938, had barely improved since the first appointment of a woman, Constantia Maxwell, in 1909. Otway-Ruthven resented this discrimination: 'We were paid less than men doing the equivalent work, and I have been told that this was right since … we were less useful to the College.'<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Otway-Ruthven|first=Annette Jocelyn|date=1977|title=Women in College 1927-77|journal=Trinity Trust News|volume=2}}</ref>
A former student, [[James Lydon (historian)|James Lydon]] (1928-2013), who later became a colleague of Otway-Ruthven at Trinity, said of her that ‘her contribution to Irish history ... will never be surpassed.’<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lydon|first=James|date=1980|title=Professor A.J.Otway-Ruthven|url=|journal=Trinity Trust News|volume=5, 2|pages=|via=}}</ref> Lydon also noted her kindness to students who were in difficulties. One of her most distinguished students was [[F. S. L. Lyons|F.S.L. Lyons]], who later became [[Provost (education)|provost]] of Trinity.{{cn|date=April 2018}}
==Select publications== Otway-Ruthven's area of particular interest was Ireland in the [[twelfth century]] and the impact on the country of the [[Anglo-Norman invasion of Ireland|arrival of the Anglo-Normans]]. She published extensively and her monograph ''A history of medieval Ireland'', was a landmark in Irish historiography.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A history of medieval Ireland|last=Otway-Ruthven|first=Annette Jocelyn|publisher=Benn|year=1980|isbn=0510278000|location=London|pages=}}</ref> She translated the Cambridgeshire [[Domesday Book]] in 1941 and the ''Liber Primus Kilkenniensis''.,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Otway-Ruthven|first=Annette Jocelyn|date=1961|title=Liber primus Kilkenniensis|url=|journal=Kilkenny Journal|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> she published [[Dowdall]] deeds with Charles McNeill in 1960 and brought a calendar of the Talbot de Malahide papers close to completion.{{cn|date=April 2018}}
Otway-Ruthven also engaged in a project to reconstruct, from transcripts in London, Irish chancery rolls which had been lost in the destruction of the [[Public Record Office of Ireland]] in the [[Irish War of Independence]] in 1922. Her work in this regard was acknowledged when the project was brought to completion in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chancery.tcd.ie/|title=Welcome To CIRCLE - CIRCLE|website=chancery.tcd.ie}}</ref> She was appointed to the [[Irish Manuscripts Commission]] in 1943 and was elected [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society|FRHS]] in 1941 and [[Member of the Royal Irish Academy|MRIA]] in 1951. She was a member of the International Commission for the History of Representative and Parliamentary Institutions.
== Personal and later life == Otway-Ruthven was an amateur [[botanist]], raising rare plants in her garden at [[Rathgar]], and was also proficient in [[needlework]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of Irish Biography|last=McGuire|first=James|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2009|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>
Shortly after her retirement in 1980 she was incapacitated by a severe [[stroke]] which left her paralysed and near-speechless. The rest of her life was spent in a nursing home, where she died on 18 March 1989. Her papers are deposited in Trinity College, and the College has a portrait of her by the artist [[Derek Hill (painter)|Derek Hill]]. The College is also home to the Castle-Otway Harp, an eighteenth-century Irish musical instrument which, although it has no known association with the family, was in [[Castle Otway]] from the mid nineteenth century.
