'''John L. Langdon''' (December 24, 1944 – December 31, 2016)<ref name=EdmontonJ>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/edmontonjournal/obituary.aspx?pid=183806940 John Langdon] ''[[Edmonton Journal]]'' (January 30, 2017)</ref> was a British-born Canadian economic and social historian of medieval England.
==Career== Langdon undertook his doctoral work at the [[University of Birmingham]], UK<ref name=EdmontonJ /> under the supervision of [[Christopher Dyer]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Horses, Oxen and Technological Innovation: The Use of Draught Animals in English Farming from 1066-1500|last=Langdon|first=John|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1986|isbn=0 521 26772 2|location=Cambridge, UK|pages=xiii}}</ref> He worked at the [[University of Alberta]], Canada (1984–2010), being appointed professor of history and classics in 1995.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/registrar/~/media/registrar/pdfcal/99calendarpdf/Staff.pdf |title=University Staff |publisher=University of Alberta |accessdate=8 April 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.registrar.ualberta.ca/calendar-archive/calendar-2015-2016/University-Staff/Emeriti/251.html |title=University Staff |publisher=University of Alberta |accessdate=8 April 2018 }}</ref>
He is best known for his contributions on medieval English technology, chiefly his book, ''Horses, Oxen and Technological Innovation: The Use of Draught Animals in English Farming from 1066–1500'' ([[Cambridge University Press]], 1986)<ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Horses, Oxen, and Technological Innovation: The Use of Draught Animals in English Farming from 1066-1500 by John Langdon |journal=[[Agricultural History (journal)|Agricultural History]] |author=Elaine Clark |year= 1987 |volume=61 |pages=80–81 |registration=yes |jstor=3743899 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Horses, Oxen and Technological Innovation: The Use of Draught Animals in English Farming from 1066-1500 by John Langdon |journal=[[The Journal of Interdisciplinary History]] |author=Richard W. Unger |year=1988 |volume=19 |pages=307–08 |doi=10.2307/204676 |registration=yes |jstor=204676 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Horses, Oxen and Technological Innovation: The Use of Draught Animals in English Farming from 1066-1500 by John Langdon |journal=[[Albion: A Quarterly Journal Concerned with British Studies]] |author=Robert S. Gottfried |year=1988 |volume=20 |pages=80–81 |doi=10.2307/4049802 |registration=yes |jstor=4049802 }}</ref> and ''Mills in the Medieval Economy: England 1300–1540'' ([[Oxford University Press]], 2004).<ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Mills in the Medieval Economy: England 1300–1540 by John Langdon |journal=[[The Economic History Review]] |author=Ben Dodds |year=2005 |volume=58 |pages=408–09 |doi= |registration=yes |jstor=3698699 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Mills in the Medieval Economy: England 1300–1540 by John Langdon |journal=[[Technology and Culture]] |author=Richard W. Unger |year=2005 |volume=46 |pages=636–38 |doi= |registration=yes |jstor=40060918 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Reviewed Work: Mills in the Medieval Economy: England 1300–1540 by John Langdon |journal=[[The English Historical Review]] |author=James Davis |year=2006 |volume=121 |pages=193–95 |doi= |registration=yes |jstor=3806248 }}</ref> He has also co-edited a number of books. With [[Grenville G. Astill]], he edited ''Medieval Farming and Technology: The Impact of Agricultural Change in Northwest Europe'' ([[Brill Publishers|Brill]], 1997). With Richard Goddard and Miriam Müller he edited a [[festschrift]] for Professor Christopher Dyer: ''Survival and Discord in Medieval Society, Essays in Honour of Christopher Dyer.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Survival and Discord in Medieval Society: Essays in Honour of Christopher Dyer|last=|first=|publisher=Brepols|year=2010|isbn=978-2-503-52815-1|location=Turnhout|pages=}}</ref> Together with Maryanne Kowaleski and Phillipp R. Schofield he edited a festschrift for Professor Bruce Campbell: ''Peasants and Lords in the Medieval English Economy: Essays in Honour of Bruce M.S. Campbell.''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Peasants and Lords in the Medieval English Economy: Essays in Honour of Bruce M.S Campbell|last=|first=|publisher=Brepols|year=2015|isbn=978-2-503-55156-2|location=Turnhout|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Forrest|first=Ian|date=2017-08-24|title=Peasants and Lords in the Medieval English Economy: Essays in Honour of Bruce M.S. Campbell, ed. Maryanne Kowaleski, John Langdon and Phillipp R. Schofield|url=https://academic.oup.com/ehr/article-abstract/132/558/1299/4093219|journal=The English Historical Review|language=en|volume=132|issue=558|pages=1299–1301|doi=10.1093/ehr/cex220|issn=0013-8266}}</ref>
