'''''The Medieval Translator''''' (French ''Traduire au Moyen Age'') is an annual volume of studies dedicated to translation in the [[Middle Ages]] and the study of translation of medieval texts. First published in 1991, it has been published since 1996 by [[Brepols]]. The volume comprises a [[Proceedings|collection of papers]] read at the Cardiff Conference on the Theory and Practice of Translation in the Middle Ages.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Brown (historian) |title=A Companion to Medieval English Literature and Culture, c.1350–c.1500 |year=2009 |publisher=Wiley |isbn=978-1-4051-9552-2 |page=138 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mp7j_xqKQ9IC&pg=PA138}}</ref> The first four volumes were edited solely by Roger Ellis,<ref>{{cite book|last=Djordjevic|first=Ivana|title=Medieval insular romance: translation and innovation|year=2000|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=978-0-85991-597-7|page=22|chapter=Mappint Medieval Translation|editors=Judith Weiss, Jennifer Fellows and Morgan Dickson|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DpeuVPJ6NScC&pg=PA22}}</ref> who is currently a general editor, with C. Batt and R. Tixier.

