{{original research|date=October 2011}} {{ref improve|date=October 2011}} The '''Y1C Problem''' or the '''Year 100 problem''' was a potential problem involving [[computers]] and [[computer systems]] in [[Taiwan]] in the night of 31 December 2010 and 1 January 2011.<ref>[http://pinyin.info/news/2006/taiwans-y1c-problem/ Pinyin news » Taiwan’s Y1C problem<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
Similar to the [[Y2K]] problem faced by much of the world in the lead-up to 2000, the Y1C problem is a side effect of Taiwan's use of the [[Minguo calendar]] for official purposes. This calendar is based on the founding of the Republic of China in 1912 (year 1), so the year 2011 on the Western [[Gregorian calendar]] corresponds to year 100 on Taiwan's official calendar, which posed potential problems for any program that only treats years as two-digit values.<ref>[http://y100.dgbas.gov.tw/y100/faq/faq.asp Y1C problem FAQ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313141209/http://y100.dgbas.gov.tw/y100/faq/faq.asp |date=March 13, 2010 }}, Minguo Year 100 Problem Service Web (Traditional Chinese), Retrieve at 2010-04-27</ref>
==Reported problems== As generally speaking only governmental offices used the official system, Y1C computer bug impact on the private sector was minimal. The potential to affect government systems was another matter. However, a large number of governmental computers were already using a three-digit system for dates, with a zero being used as the first digit for years below 100 (Gregorian 2010 or earlier).
Some government documents such as driver's licenses already refer to years over 100; nothing more than minor glitches were reported.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
Some [[iPhone]] users reported that their alarm tool failed to function on 1 January 2011.<ref>[http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2011/new/jan/2/today-life8.htm 百年蟲作怪 100年變00年]</ref>{{clarification needed|date=December 2014}}
==North Korea== The [[North Korean calendar|North Korean (''Juche'') calendar]] was affected the same day as Taiwan's, as North Korea's calendar is also based on an event that happened in 1912 - the [[birthday of Kim Il-sung]].
==See also== * [[Time formatting and storage bugs]]
